					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/sirpudding" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(348648); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=348648&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251710" alt="sirpudding" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=348648)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/sirpudding" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(348648); return false;" >sirpudding</a></span> <span class="odate time_1492537339 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">18 Apr 2017 17:42</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2795000">
									

<p>The sex/gender confusion seems to stem from Victorians being afraid to say &quot;sex&quot; and English having lost most of its gendering.</p>
<p>In German, for example, girls are neutral, youths (male or female) are masculine, and maidens are feminine. None of which has a whit to do with genotype or phenotype.</p>
<p>Incidentally, genotypical sex based on chromosomes and phenotypical sex (i.e. development of primary and secondary sexual characteristics) aren't always strongly correlated, and more complex than simply dimorphic besides.</p>

							</div>

								
